Many of the attacks in Kabul have been
blamed on the Haqqani network, an al Qaida and Taliban-linked movement 
that operates out of Pakistan.

The
confirmation of the dead Brits follows the announcement that 12 
Americans and a Canadian were killed on Saturday when a Taliban suicide 
bomber struck a coalition vehicle in Afghanistan’s capital.

Four U.S. troops and one Canadian solider died in the blast as well as eight American civilian contractors.

It
is the deadliest attack on the U.S.-led coalition in Kabul since the 
war began and is a major setback for the alliance as it begins to scale 
back combat troops.

